Egypt’s ENPPI were unbeaten throughout the just concluded ITTF African Club Championships to retain their men’s team title ahead of youthful Remo Stars of Nigeria. Nigeria Security and Civil Defense Corps (NSCDC) had to work hard to emerge as the women’s team championships after beating Ocean View 3-2 in the final. The Egypt’s ENPPI led by their French import Antoine Hachard proved too strong for the host team Remo Stars as the visitors won 3-0 to retain their trophy.   Salah: I’ll be at Liverpool next season for sure     Falcons’ Nnadozie wins top French Women’s league award     Zenith Bank tennis grand slam enters crucial stages   Meanwhile, number one seed Quadri Aruna will begin campaign in the 2022 Africa Cup alongside Egypt’s Omar Assar and world number one in U15 and U-17 14-year-old Hana Goda of Egypt. According to the draws, the 28 male players have been drawn into eight groups with the top two advancing to the knockout stage. The ITTF Competition Manager Mohamed El-Dawlatly said the quality of the players would give fans the opportunity of watching exciting matches. “I am so excited with the atmosphere in Lagos especially with the presence of fans on daily basis as the just concluded Club Championships has given us an idea of what to expect in the Africa Cup,” he said.“I look forward to the ever-supporting Lagos fans and I believe we will have an explosive competition this year with the best emerging as champions.”